# Cline Rules for Telegram Bot Project
# =======================================

## Project Overview
- This is a Node.js/JavaScript Telegram bot project
- Located at: e:/Programming/workspace/mcps/telegram-lm-interface
- Repository: https://github.com/Ib-R/telegram-lm-interface.git
- Uses workspaces configuration with "telegram" hint

## Code Style & Conventions
- Use modern JavaScript/ES6+ syntax
- Follow consistent naming conventions (camelCase for variables/functions, PascalCase for classes)
- Keep functions focused and single-purpose
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Add JSDoc comments for complex functions and public APIs

## File Organization
- Don't ever edit .env file
- Keep related functionality in logical modules
- Separate concerns: models, controllers, routes, services, utilities
- Use index.js as the main entry point
- Follow existing project structure patterns

## Security Considerations
- Never commit secrets or API keys (use .env.example pattern)
- Validate all user inputs from Telegram
- Implement proper error handling without leaking sensitive info
- Sanitize user data before storing in database
- Use environment variables for configuration (.env file not committed)

## Testing
- Write tests for critical functions and business logic
- Maintain good test coverage for core features
- Test edge cases and error scenarios
- Don't write tests for trivial utilities or one-liners

## Documentation
- Keep README.md up to date with project status and instructions
- Add inline comments explaining complex logic
- Document API endpoints if applicable
- Include usage examples where helpful

## Bot-Specific Rules
- Handle Telegram Webhook errors gracefully (HTTP 401, etc.)
- Use long-polling as fallback when webhooks fail
- Implement rate limiting for API calls
- Handle unknown/removed users in updates
- Cache frequently accessed data to reduce API calls

## Optimization Guidelines
- Avoid unnecessary re-fetching of Telegram user data
- Batch database operations where possible
- Implement pagination for list endpoints
- Use Redis or similar for shared state if needed

## Development Workflow
- Make small, focused commits
- Write descriptive commit messages
- Update related files when making changes
- Ensure build passes before committing
- Run linters/tests locally before push

## Common Tasks Priority
1. Fix bugs first
2. Add tests for critical paths
3. Update documentation as needed
4. Optimize performance only after functionality is solid
5. Refactor dead code or technical debt when it makes sense
